<a name="0">[0]</a> <a href="#0" id=0>In this we try to understand the behavior of a system by ascribing to it beliefs, goals, intentions, likes and dislikes, and other mental qualities.</a>
<a name="1">[1]</a> <a href="#1" id=1>This article is about when we're right or almost right in saying these things, and when it's a good idea to think of machines that way.</a>
<a name="2">[2]</a> <a href="#2" id=2>It also isn't shorthand for a specific prediction of what the dog is likely to do next.</a>
<a name="3">[3]</a> <a href="#3" id=3>It is amusing that we can't attribute a purpose for the existence of ants, but we can find a purpose for the glands in an ant that emit a chemical substance for other ants to follow.</a>
<a name="4">[4]</a> <a href="#4" id=4>In this we analyze something in terms of the purpose for which it is designed.</a>
<a name="5">[5]</a> <a href="#5" id=5>For example, it doesn't commit a person to any position about whether the dog has the mental machinery to know that it is a dog or even to know that it wants to go out.</a>
<a name="6">[6]</a> <a href="#6" id=6>The intentional stance is most useful when it is the only way of expressing what we know about a system.</a>
<a name="7">[7]</a> <a href="#7" id=7>The statement isn't shorthand for something the dog did, because there are many ways of knowing that a dog wants to go out.</a>
<a name="8">[8]</a> <a href="#8" id=8>In general we cannot give definitions, because the concepts form a system that we fit as a whole to phenomena.</a>
<a name="9">[9]</a> <a href="#9" id=9>And if all we wanted to think about were zero and one, we wouldn't bother with the concept of number.</a>
<a name="10">[10]</a> <a href="#10" id=10>Anthropomorphism is the ascription of human characteristics to things not human.</a>
